{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "IntroductionIn the rapidly evolving world of Artificial Intelligence (AI), Large Language Models (LLMs) have emerged as a cornerstone of generative AI, driving advancements in natural language processing, content generation, and beyond [1,2,3,4].",
    "However, one of the most significant challenges facing LLMs is their static knowledge base, which, once trained, does not naturally evolve with the emergence of new information [5,6,7].",
    "This limitation not only curtails the model's relevance over time but also restricts its ability to generate up-to-date and accurate content.",
    "The conventional approach to address this issue involves periodically retraining the model with new data, a process that is not only resource-intensive but also impractical for real-time knowledge updating [2].",
    "Furthermore, the pace at which information grows and changes in the digital era means that the window of relevance for these models is rapidly shrinking, requiring a more dynamic approach to knowledge management [8,9].Enter GPT-Neo, an open-source alternative to the proprietary GPT models, which has garnered attention for its adaptability and performance in generative tasks."
  ],
